04795nam a22007815i 9780823280179DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232801797 a10.1515/97808232801792doi  a(DE-B1597)555269  a(OCoLC)1035845119  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0671102bisacsh04a233/.52231 aMeyer, Eric Daryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInner Animalities :bTheology and the End of the Human /cEric Daryl Meyer. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGroundworks: Ecological Issues in Philosophy and Theology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Critical and Historical Animalities -- t1. Gregory of Nazianzus: Animality and Ascent -- t2. Gregory of Nyssa: Reading Animality and Desire -- t3. The Problem of Human Animality in Contemporary Theological Anthropology -- tPART II. Constructive A nimalities -- t4. Animality and Identity: Human Nature and the Image of God -- t5. Animality in Sin and Redemption -- t6. Animality in Eschatological Transformation -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost theology proceeds under the assumption that divine grace works on human beings at the points of our supposed uniqueness among earth’s creatures—our freedom, our self-awareness, our language, or our rationality. Inner Animalities turns this assumption on its head. Arguing that much theological anthropology contains a deeply anti-ecological impulse, the book draws creatively on historical and scriptural texts to imagine an account of human life centered in our creaturely commonality.The tendency to deny our own human animality leaves our self-understanding riven with contradictions, disavowals, and repressions. How are human relationships transformed when God draws us into communion through our instincts, our desires, and our bodily needs? Meyer argues that humanity’s exceptional status is not the result of divine endorsement, but a delusion of human sin. Where the work of God knits human beings back into creaturely connections, ecological degradation is no longer just a matter of bodily life and death, but a matter of ultimate significance.Bringing a theological perspective to the growing field of Critical Animal Studies, Inner Animalities puts Gregory of Nyssa and Karl Rahner in conversation with Jacques Derrida, Giorgio Agamben, Kelly Oliver, and Cary Wolfe. What results is not only a counterintuitive account of human life in relation with nonhuman neighbors, but also a new angle into ecological theology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aTheological anthropologyxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Systematic.2bisacsh  aAnimals.  aCritical Animal Studies.  aEcological Theology.  aGiorgio Agamben.  aGregory of Nazianzus.  aGregory of Nyssa.  aImage of God.  aJacques Derrida.  aOriginal Sin.  aResurrection of the Body.  aTheological Anthropology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823280179zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823280179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823280179/original  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE 